- I have deployed my application on an EC2 instance, but users are getting a 500 Internal Server Error when accessing it through the URL. 
How would you troubleshoot it?
==> A 500 Internal Server Error means the request reached the server, but the application failed to process it. I would first verify that the application service 
is running, then review the application logs and web server logs to identify the root cause. Next, I would test the application locally using curl, 
verify the reverse proxy configuration, check database connectivity, and review CPU, memory, and disk utilization on the EC2 instance. If a Load Balancer is 
involved, I would also verify target health and Security Group rules. By troubleshooting each layer systematically, I can quickly isolate and resolve the issue.

- There is an EBS volume managed by Terraform for multiple environments (Dev, Staging, Prod). When I run terraform plan, it always shows changes to the EBS 
tags even though I haven't modified anything. How would you fix it?
==> If Terraform keeps showing tag changes for an EBS volume, I would first review the terraform plan output to identify which tags are changing. Then I would 
compare the environment-specific variables, check for configuration drift caused by manual changes in AWS, and verify whether provider default_tags are applied 
consistently. If Terraform is the source of truth, I would apply the changes. If the tags are intentionally managed outside Terraform, I would use a lifecycle 
{ ignore_changes = [tags] } block to prevent unnecessary updates.

